# To confine in, or as in, a pound; to impound.
#* '''1644''', {{w|John Milton}}, ''{{w|Areopagitica}}; A speech of Mr. John Milton for the Liberty of Unlicenc’d Printing, to the Parlament of England''
#*: And he who were pleasantly disposed, could not well avoid to liken it to the exploit of that gallant man, who thought to '''pound''' up the crows by shutting his park gate.

===Etymology 3===
From an alteration of earlier {{term|poun|lang=en}}, {{term|pown|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|pounen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|pūnian||to pound, beat, bray, bruise, crush}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*pūnōną||to break to pieces, pulverise}}. Related to {{etyl|stq|-}} {{term|Pün||debris, fragments|lang=stq}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|puin||debris, fragments, rubbish|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|pun||fragments|lang=nds}}. Perhaps influenced by '''Etymology 2''' {{etyl|enm|-}} {{m|enm|*pound}}, {{term|pond|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|*pund}}, {{term|pynd|lang=ang}}, in relation to the hollow [[mortar]] for pounding with the [[pestle]].

====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|poun}}, {{l|en|pown}} {{qualifier|obsolete or dialectal}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{label|en|transitive}} To strike hard, usually repeatedly.
#* {{quote-book|year=1913|author={{w|Joseph C. Lincoln}}|chapter=12
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL5535161W Mr. Pratt's Patients]
|passage=She had Lord James' collar in one big fist and she '''pounded''' the table with the other and talked a blue streak. Nobody could make out plain what she said, for she was mainly jabbering Swede lingo, but there was English enough, of a kind, to give us some idee.}}
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[crush]] to pieces; to [[pulverize]].
# {{label|en|transitive|slang}} To eat or drink very quickly.
#: {{ux|en|You really '''pounded''' that beer!}}
# {{label|en|transitive|baseball|slang}} To [[pitch]] consistently to a certain location.
#: {{ux|en|The pitcher has been '''pounding''' the outside corner all night.}}
# {{label|en|intransitive|of a body part, generally heart, blood, or head}} To [[beat]] strongly or [[throb]].
#: {{ux|en|As I tiptoed past the sleeping dog, my heart was '''pounding''' but I remained silent.}}
#: {{ux|en|My head was '''pounding'''.}}
# {{label|en|transitive|slang}} To [[penetrate]] [[sexual]]ly, with [[vigour]].
#: {{ux|en|I was '''pounding''' her all night!}}
# To advance heavily with measured steps.
#* '''1899''', {{w|Joseph Conrad}}, ''[[s:Heart of Darkness|Heart of Darkness]]'', [[s:Heart of Darkness/Section I|section 1]]
#*: We '''pounded''' along, stopped, landed soldiers; went on, landed custom–house clerks to levy toll in what looked like a God–forsaken wilderness, with a tin shed and a flag–pole lost in it; landed more soldiers—to take care of the custom–house clerks, presumably.
# {{label|en|engineering}} To make a [[jarring]] [[noise]], as when running.
#: {{ux|en|The engine '''pounds'''.}}
# {{context|slang|dated|lang=en}}  To [[wager]] a [[pound]] on. 
#* '''1854''', Dickens, ''Hard Times'', Chapter 4:
#*: Good-bye, my dear!' said Sleary. 'You'll make your fortun, I hope, and none of our poor folkth will ever trouble you, I'll '''pound''' it.  

