==English==
{{slim-wikipedia|Pie (disambiguation)}}
[[Image:Lemon Meringue Pie 1.jpg|thumb|Unsliced lemon meringue pie.]]

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US|UK}} {{enPR|pī}}, {{IPA|/paɪ/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-pie.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{homophones|pi|π|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|aɪ|lang=en}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, unknown origin.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# A type of [[pastry]] that consists of an outer crust and a [[filling]].
#: ''The family had steak and kidney '''pie''' for dinner and cherry '''pie''' for dessert.''
# Any of various other, non-pastry dishes that maintain the general concept of a shell with a filling.
#: ''Shepherd's '''pie''' is made of mince covered with mashed potato.''
# {{context|Northeastern US|lang=en}} [[pizza|Pizza]].
# {{context|figuratively|lang=en}} The [[whole]] of a wealth or [[resource]], to be divided in parts.
#* ''It is easier to get along when everyone, more or less, is getting ahead. But when the '''pie''' is shrinking, social groups are more likely to turn on each other.'' &mdash; [[w:Evan Thomas|Evan Thomas]], ''[http://www.newsweek.com/2010/12/04/the-deepest-dangers-facing-the-united-states.html Why It’s Time to Worry]'', Newsweek 2010-12-04
# {{context|letterpress|lang=en}} A disorderly mess of spilt [[type]].
# {{context|cricket|lang=en}} An especially badly [[bowl]]ed ball.
# {{context|pejorative|lang=en}} a [[gluttonous]] person.
# A [[pie chart]].
#* '''1986''', Carolyn Sorensen, ‎Henry J. Stock, ''Department of Education Computer Graphics Guide'' (page 8)
#*: '''Pies''' are best for comparing the components of only one or two totals.
# {{context|slang|lang=en}} The [[vulva]].
#* '''1981''', William Kotzwinkle, ''Jack in the Box''
#*: "Yeah, take it off!" "SHOW US YOUR '''PIE'''!" The brunette opened the catch on her G-string and let the sequinned cloth slip down, teasing them with it.
#* '''2010''', W. A. Moltinghorne, ''Magnolia Park'' (page 238)
#*: Yeah, some guys like to eat the old hairy '''pie'''. Women, too, or so I've heard.

